"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100491","Attorney General","false","2014-10-28","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer I gave to the Hon. Member for Dwyfor Meirionnydd on 23<sup>rd</sup> October 2014 (questions, 211141, 211143 and 211144). The previous answer included tables detailing the number of offences charged under Sections 4A(1)(a)(b)(i), Sections 4A(1)(a)(b)(ii) and 2A(1) of the 1997 Act broken down by each police force in England and Wales.</p>","South Swindon","Mr Robert Buckland","211533","2014-10-28T13:17:54.7648416Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100491/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100491/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100491/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-10-22","Stalking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many people have been charged under the provisions of section 4a of the Protection from Harassment Act 1997 since 25 November 2012.","true","Biography information for Ms Nadine Dorries","Mid Bedfordshire","Nadine Dorries","211534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100492","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-27","<p>The Government does not tolerate violence of any kind in young offender institutions and assaults are treated extremely seriously. The National Offender Management Service (NOMS) is comprehensively reviewing how it manages violence and will issue revised guidance in 2015. NOMS is also working with the police and Crown Prosecution Service to improve the investigation and prosecution of crime in young offender institutions and prisons.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to reducing self-harm in young offender institutions. All young offender institutions and prisons are required to have procedures in place to identify, manage and support people who are at risk of harm to themselves. These procedures include the Assessment, Care in Custody and Teamwork (ACCT) process, which is an offender-centred, flexible care planning system designed to ensure that offenders at risk are managed in a way that is responsive to individual needs, including those related to age.</p><p> </p><p>An analysis of assaults and self-harm by age is included in the Safety in Custody Statistics Bulletin, available at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/safety-in-custody-statistics" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/safety-in-custody-statistics</a>.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","211569","2014-10-27T16:05:06.8138633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100492/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100492/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100492/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-22","Young Offender Institutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps the Government is taking to prevent violence in young offenders institutions.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","211568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100493","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-27","<p>The Government does not tolerate violence of any kind in young offender institutions and assaults are treated extremely seriously. The National Offender Management Service (NOMS) is comprehensively reviewing how it manages violence and will issue revised guidance in 2015. NOMS is also working with the police and Crown Prosecution Service to improve the investigation and prosecution of crime in young offender institutions and prisons.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to reducing self-harm in young offender institutions. All young offender institutions and prisons are required to have procedures in place to identify, manage and support people who are at risk of harm to themselves. These procedures include the Assessment, Care in Custody and Teamwork (ACCT) process, which is an offender-centred, flexible care planning system designed to ensure that offenders at risk are managed in a way that is responsive to individual needs, including those related to age.</p><p> </p><p>An analysis of assaults and self-harm by age is included in the Safety in Custody Statistics Bulletin, available at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/safety-in-custody-statistics" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/safety-in-custody-statistics</a>.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","211568","2014-10-27T16:05:06.9076528Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100493/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100493/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100493/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-22","Young Offenders: Self-harm","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps the Government is taking to prevent self-harm in young offenders institutions.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","211569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100494","Department of Health","false","2014-10-27","<p>NHS England has responsibility for commissioning health services in young offenders’ institutions (YOIs). NHS England has worked closely with the Royal Colleges of Paediatrics and Child Health; General Practitioners; Nursing; Psychiatrists and Forensic Medicine and has used their standards for children and young people in secure settings as a basis for national service specifications for the health services commissioned in YOIs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A key component of this is that the service should deliver child and adolescent mental health services (CAMHS) which meet the emotional and mental health needs of children and young people accommodated within the secure setting, based on clinical need. Children in secure settings are entitled to service provision that is equivalent to that available for children living in the wider community, within the constraints of the secure environment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>CAMHS cover early intervention, mental health promotion, prevention and treatment for the full range of mental health needs and care after discharge from a secure placement, including transfer to inpatient or adult services.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The CHAT (Comprehensive Health Assessment Tool) is used as a health screen for all children and young people entering the secure estate to assess individual health need and identify those needing a full mental health assessment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-10-27T16:56:44.291591Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100494/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100494/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100494/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-22","Young Offender Institutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps the Government is taking to (a) treat and (b) prevent depression in young offenders institutions.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","211570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100495","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-27","<p /> <p>The Government is committed to providing emotional support to young people and young adults in Young Offender Institutions (YOIs). All young offender institutions and prisons are required to have procedures in place to identify, manage and support offenders in need of emotional support or at risk of harming themselves.</p><p> </p><p>These procedures include the Assessment, Care in Custody and Teamwork (ACCT) process which is an offender-centred, flexible care planning system designed to ensure that offenders at risk are managed in a way that is responsive to individual needs, including those related to age. A recent review of the ACCT process for young people made a number of recommendations that are being taken forward by the National Offender Management Service.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England provide a commissioned healthcare service to all YOIs which includes GPs, nurses and mental health professionals to support those with an identified physical or mental health need in custody. Support services provided under contract are equitable with those provided in the community.</p><p> </p><p>Healthcare services are supported by the chaplaincy team which offers a range of pastoral support services and by the Samaritans who provide free helpline access and train young offenders aged 18 and over to act as ‘Listeners’, that is, peer supporters for other young offenders who are in crisis.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-27T16:11:26.5118239Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100495/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100495/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100495/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-22","Young Offenders: Counselling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps the Government is taking to provide emotional support for inmates of young offenders institutions.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","211571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100496","Attorney General","false","2014-10-28","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer I gave to the Hon. Member for Dwyfor Meirionnydd on 23<sup>rd</sup> October 2014 (questions, 211141, 211143 and 211144). The previous answer included tables detailing the number of offences charged under Sections 4A(1)(a)(b)(i), Sections 4A(1)(a)(b)(ii) and 2A(1) of the 1997 Act broken down by each police force in England and Wales.</p>","South Swindon","Mr Robert Buckland","211534","2014-10-28T13:17:54.542166Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100496/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100496/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-10-22","Stalking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many people have been charged under the provisions of section 2a of the Protection from Harassment Act 1997 since 25 November 2012.","true","Biography information for Ms Nadine Dorries","Mid Bedfordshire","Nadine Dorries","211533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100497","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-27","<p /> <p>When sentencing a child or young person under the age 18, courts have a duty to have regard to the welfare of the offender, which includes their mental health.</p><p> </p><p>Youth Offending Teams provide courts with a pre-sentence report for each young person, including information about their mental health and any self-harming or risk taking behaviour. Where emotional and mental health issues have been identified, a referral to the mental health specialist worker should be made for completion of a Comprehensive Health Assessment Tool which will provide details about the support and type of intervention programme needed, tailored to their needs. The pre-sentence report should assess the potential impact of any custodial sentence imposed by the court (including the impact on mental health).</p><p> </p><p>In January 2014, the Government announced £25 million of funding for the Liaison and Diversion Programme, which will join up police and courts with mental health services and to fund the provision of mental health professionals to give prompt and appropriate treatment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This Programme, commissioned by NHS England, identifies, assesses and refers people of all ages with a wide range of mental health and other issues on first contact with the criminal justice system. A person assessed with single or multiple vulnerabilities will be referred to the appropriate treatment or support service and care and/or support will be instigated.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-27T16:33:45.3017773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100497/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100497/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100497/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-22","Young Offenders: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps the Government is taking to prevent young people with mental illnesses and depression from being sentenced to custody in young offenders institutions.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","211572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100498","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-28","<p>I refer the right hon. Member to the answer given on 17 June by my predecessor as Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Justice, my right hon. Friend the Member for Kenilworth and Southam (Jeremy Wright) <em>Official Report</em>, column 584W.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-28T14:34:26.6072078Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100498/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100498/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100498/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-22","Stalking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of probation staff have received training in sections 2A and 4A of the Protection from Harassment Act 1997.","false","Biography information for Mr Elfyn Llwyd","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Mr Elfyn Llwyd","211651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100499","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-28","<p>Staff employed in the Prison Service Reserve are mobile as a condition of service, and can, therefore, be permanently transferred to any civil service post. All NOMS staff can be required to serve periods of detached duty. Decisions on suitability for redeployment or detached duty will take account of an employee’s individual circumstances.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","211649","2014-10-28T14:49:38.5189714Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100499/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100499/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-22","Prison Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether staff employed in the Prison Service Reserve can be ordered to perform detached duty.","false","Biography information for Mr Elfyn Llwyd","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Mr Elfyn Llwyd","211650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100500","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-28","<p>The creation of the Prison Service Reserve was announced in June. Staff information will be published in late November, covering the period up to 30 September.</p><p> </p><p>Recruitment for both the Prison Service Reserves and for permanent officers is progressing well. NOMS is currently aiming to appoint around 100 Reserves (full time equivalents), but with the flexibility to develop the Reserve as required. We will also be recruiting nearly 1,700 Prison Officers on permanent contracts between 1 January 2014 to 31 March 2015.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-28T17:24:44.487682Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100500/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100500/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-22","Prison Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many Prison Service Reserve Band 4 staff have been employed at each prison establishment in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Elfyn Llwyd","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Mr Elfyn Llwyd","211648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100501","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-28","<p>Staff employed in the Prison Service Reserve are mobile as a condition of service, and can, therefore, be permanently transferred to any civil service post. All NOMS staff can be required to serve periods of detached duty. Decisions on suitability for redeployment or detached duty will take account of an employee’s individual circumstances.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","211650","2014-10-28T14:49:38.3939909Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100501/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100501/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100501/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-22","Prison Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether staff employed in the Prison Service Reserve are classed as mobile grades as defined by the Civil Service Management Code.","false","Biography information for Mr Elfyn Llwyd","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Mr Elfyn Llwyd","211649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100502","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-29","<p /> <p>On arrival in an establishment, the risk a prisoner presents to others and themselves, and their risk of harm from other prisoners will be assessed. Where appropriate, this will include a Cell Sharing Risk Assessment to assess a prisoner’s suitability to share accommodation. The risk assessment will consider information and intelligence from a number of sources, including known gang affiliations and conflicts if appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>In April 2014, NOMS completed the implementation of a nationally networked intelligence system - ‘Mercury’. Through the Mercury system staff are able to access intelligence linked to prisoners where a prisoner has previously been held in custody, on or in advance of a prisoner’s arrival (where a prisoner is being sent from another establishment). In addition where a prisoner has previously been held in custody, the National Offender Management Information System (NOMIS) will hold warnings to alert staff to particular risks and behaviours.</p><p> </p><p>A number of law enforcement agencies, including the police, regularly share information about prisoners to support the identification of risk. This includes prisoners with gang affiliations and conflicts.</p><p> </p><p>To ensure that prisoners are held in safe, decent and secure conditions, the risks to and from prisoners remain constantly under review. Where risks become known, establishments take appropriate steps to mitigate these risks, which may include relocating a prisoner to another wing or establishment.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-29T17:52:58.6696583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100502/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100502/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100502/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-22","Prisons: Organised Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he is taking to increase gang-related intelligence for prison officers prior to prisoner arrivals in order to prevent mixed gang wings.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","211643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100503","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-29","<p /> <p>A specialised system of restraint known as control and restraint (C&amp;R) has been developed over many years to ensure that prisoners can be controlled with minimum risk of injury to staff or prisoners. C&amp;R is a system of techniques used by a team of three officers as a last resort to bring a violent or unmanageable prisoner under control. Wherever possible staff are instructed to avoid use of force and de-escalate the situation by persuasion or negotiation. If the techniques are applied they are used for as short a time as possible.</p><p> </p><p>All prisons submit a central monthly return providing the number of times force has been used in the prison, and specifically the number of uses of C&amp;R. While this has been collated centrally since late 2009, to provide details since 2004 could only be achieved at disproportionate cost, as it would require contacting every prison individually and tracing data from prisons that have closed since 2004.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-29T17:50:21.6820186Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100503/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100503/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100503/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-22","Prisons: Restraint Techniques","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many control and restraint techniques have been used in prisons in each year since 2004.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","211642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100504","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-18","<p /> <p>The Chair of the independent review of veterans in the criminal justice system, Stephen Phillips, has formally met the Advisors to the review four times. A number of the advisors have attended two visits and they are also being consulted on the text of the report.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-11-18T16:59:58.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100504/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100504/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100504/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-22","Criminal Proceedings: Veterans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many times officials conducting his Department's review of veterans in the criminal justice system have formally consulted the review's Advisory Committee since the launch of the review.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","211583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100505","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-29","<p>There are no building projects planned or in delivery that are specifically intended to improve first night accommodation across the estate. Where individual first night accommodation has been identified as requiring improvement, this is taken forward locally by the Governor/Director.</p><p> </p><p>Prison Service Instruction 74/2011 Residential Services requires that prisoners have access to living accommodation, furnishings, fittings and equipment that are safe, decent and secure and which meet their individual needs, as far as practicable. Living accommodation and communal areas are also to be kept clean and maintained. Where a fault is reported residential prison staff are responsible for reporting the problem to the appropriate person for the issue to be resolved.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-29T17:49:06.9757293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100505/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100505/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100505/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-22","Prison Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he is taking to improve first night accommodation for prisoners in prisons.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","211652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100506","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-10-29","<p>None. I visited Torbay in April 2014 but this was a political visit which was arranged and paid for by the Conservative Party.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-10-29T13:00:20.5814181Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100506/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100506/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100506/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-10-22","Torbay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many visits were made by Ministers of her Department to Torbay constituency in the 12 months to October 2014; whom the invitation for each such visit was issued by; and what the cost to the public purse was of each such visit.","false","Biography information for Mr Adrian Sanders","Torbay","Mr Adrian Sanders","211531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100507","Cabinet Office","false","2014-10-24","<p>I refer the Hon Gentlemen to Departmental Business Plans which record all commitments, timescales for completion and progress against them. The Business Plans are fully transparent and are available at <a href="http://www.transparency.number10.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.transparency.number10.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin","211407","2014-10-24T12:04:47.6767103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100507/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100507/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100507/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-10-22","Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which government policies announced since the Coalition Agreement have not been implemented; and what the reason is for not implementing each such policy.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","211406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100508","Cabinet Office","false","2014-10-24","<p>I refer the Hon Gentlemen to Departmental Business Plans which record all commitments, timescales for completion and progress against them. The Business Plans are fully transparent and are available at <a href="http://www.transparency.number10.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.transparency.number10.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin","211406","2014-10-24T12:04:47.7704741Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100508/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100508/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100508/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-10-22","Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which of the policies outlined in the Coalition Agreement have not been implemented; and what the reason is for not implementing each such policy.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","211407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100509","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-29","<p>We anticipate that following the recruitment process we will be able to announce the Residents’ Commissioner in December.</p><p> </p><p>The Commissioner will report to Sir David Higgins, the Chairman of HS2 Ltd. This will create a direct link to ensure that the Commissioner’s views are heard at the highest level.</p><p> </p><p>The Commissioner will be based at HS2 Ltd’s head office in Canary Wharf and will have one staff member available to provide administrative support, as well as drawing on support from relevant teams across the organisation.　 This is a new role and so resource will be reviewed in consultation with the Commissioner once in post.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-10-29T11:20:20.1066446Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100509/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100509/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100509/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-10-22","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department plans to appoint the High Speed 2 Residents Commissioner; where that Commissioner will be based; to whom that Commissioner will be accountable; and how many staff at what level that Commissioner will have.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","211416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100510","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-28","<p>The estimated numbers of passengers on flights originating in Northern Ireland who take connecting flights from other UK airports in each of the last five years are given in the table below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p>Passengers originating in Northern Ireland who transfer at UK airports, 2009 - 2013</p><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p>Year</p><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p>Transfer passengers (000's)</p><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>571</p><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>506</p><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>400</p><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>441</p><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p><p> </p><p> </p></td><td><p>343</p><p> </p><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p /> <p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>These figures are based on data from the CAA’s passenger surveys and reflect those airports which form part of the continuous survey (Heathrow, Gatwick, Luton, Stansted and Manchester). These airports account for the majority of transfer passengers travelling from Northern Ireland.</p><p /> <p> </p><p />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-10-28T15:57:39.3613682Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100510/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100510/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100510/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-10-22","Aviation: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the number of passengers on flights originating in Northern Ireland who take connecting flights from other UK Airports in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dr Alasdair McDonnell","Belfast South","Dr Alasdair McDonnell","211412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100511","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-27","<p>No decisions have been taken regarding the procurement of electric rolling stock for the Midland Main Line. This will be a matter for the train operator. An announcement on this will be made in due course.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-10-27T14:11:52.8920331Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100511/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100511/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100511/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-10-22","Midland Main Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, from where his Department plans to secure trains to run on the Midland mainline when electrification of that line is completed.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","211462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100512","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-29","<p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency will be implementing internal plans over the next 12 months to match the resources available for the conduct of marine surveying and ship inspection activities to fulfil national and international obligations.</p><p> </p><p>This will involve improving efficiency, targeting activities based on risk, different ways of working to capitalise on technology, and maximising potential income.　 This is normal management activity to match resources to tasks and will not result in a formal report.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2014-10-29T14:49:29.1053733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100512/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100512/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100512/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-10-22","Maritime and Coastguard Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department plans to publish the conclusions of its review of the Maritime and Coastguard Agency's survey and inspection capability.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","211527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100513","HM Treasury","false","2014-10-27","<p>I refer the Honorable Gentleman to my earlier replies about VAT [DN: please insert correct reference]. Special provisions apply to Government Departments and health authorities that refunds VAT incurred on certain non-business activities. These are set out in section 41(3) of the VAT Act 1994.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>New bodies are not automatically covered by the above provisions. However, the Department for Transport and HM Treasury are considering this issue.</p><p> </p><p>Government departments are exempt from Corporation Tax, while Non-</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Departmental Public Bodies (which the Highways agency will become) are subject to Corporation Tax on any trading and investment income and on any capital gains.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-10-27T16:27:25.9402829Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100513/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100513/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100513/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-10-22","Highways Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether it is his policy that the Highways Agency, following its transfer from being a civil service agency to a government-owned company will be liable to pay (a) corporation tax and (b) additional payments of VAT.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","211500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100514","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-29","<p>The attached table shows the International Maritime Organization (IMO) number and flag of each ship, in every year between 2009 and 2013, which has been detained in UK ports following a port state control inspection by the Maritime and Coastguard Agency.</p><p> </p><p>There are many reasons why a ship can be detained. Details about the detentions for each ship can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.parismou.org/inspection-search" target="_blank">https://www.parismou.org/inspection-search</a></p><p /> <p /> <p>and searching using the ship’s IMO Number.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>In the case of a detention, the Port State Control inspector has found serious deficiencies which demonstrate that the ship does not comply substantially with the applicable requirements of the relevant International Conventions for the ship. These serious deficiencies are considered to affect the safety of the ship, or the crew or the environment or the living and working conditions on board such that the inspector has to return to the ship to verify that all the deficiencies have been rectified before departure of the ship from the UK.</p><p /> <p /> <p> </p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2014-10-29T14:48:17.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100514/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100514/answer","211528 - table - Detentions by year and flag.pdf","211528 - table - Detentions by year and flag.pdf","211528 - table of detentions by year and flag","211528 - table of detentions by year and flag","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100514/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-10-22","Shipping: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many ships the Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) has detained following an inspection conducted in line with the MCA's port state control responsibilities in each of the last five years; and what the (a) reasons for detention and (b) flag registry were in each such case.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","211528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100515","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-27","<p>The job is currently advertised on the HS2 website by clicking on the link to ‘Jobs’. The advert has been placed in the following media:</p><p> </p><p>From Thursday 23 October 2014: The Guardian newspaper and The Lawyer websites</p><p> </p><p>Friday 24 October 2014: Property Week publication – it will also appear on the Property Week website from 24 October</p><p> </p><p>Sunday 26 October 2014: Sunday Times – in print and online and on the Sunday Times iPAD version.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-10-27T17:14:30.2716989Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100515/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100515/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100515/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-10-22","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, where, when and how often the job of HS2 Resident's Commissioner will be advertised.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","211589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100516","Home Office","false","2014-11-05","<p>The Home Office publishes guidance advising hauliers on vehicle security, but also what they should do if they believe somebody is hiding in their vehicle. This guidance is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/secure-your-vehicle-to-help-stop-illegal-immigration" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/secure-your-vehicle-to-help-stop-illegal-immigration</a>. <br><br>This website also includes contact details for Border Force’s Clandestine Entrant Civil Penalty Team, from whom hauliers also receive advice.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-11-05T14:51:48.6594814Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100516/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100516/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100516/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-22","Illegal Immigrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what support his Department provides to British lorry drivers to prevent people seeking to enter the UK illegally accessing their vehicles at (a) Calais and (b) other ports of entry to the UK.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","211639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100517","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-28","<p>Network Rail is responsible for managing its estates in an operationally- effective and cost-efficient way. The choice of lighting used in Network Rail’s premises is an operational matter for the company.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has no locus to mandate the type of lighting that train operating companies use on their premises. Many depots are owned by the train manufacturers rather than by Network Rail or the train operators, as the contracts for the rolling stock often include maintenance. At stations, when lighting systems are due for renewal, they would normally be replaced with the current modern equivalent standard of lighting.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-10-28T15:54:50.8795565Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100517/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100517/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100517/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-10-22","Railways: Lighting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make it his policy to issue guidance to (a) Network Rail and (b) train operating companies that they should implement a replacement programme to introduce LED lighting in their premises.","false","Biography information for Sir Bob Russell","Colchester","Sir Bob Russell","211602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100518","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-27","<p>The Department for Transport will consider installation of LED lights during major refurbishment projects where cost effective to do so. Information on the proportion of lighting which is currently LED is not centrally recorded and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-10-27T14:10:43.8183849Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100518/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100518/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100518/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-10-22","Lighting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make it his policy to implement a replacement programme to introduce LED lights throughout his Department's buildings and sites; if he will estimate the proportion of lighting in his Department which is LED; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Bob Russell","Colchester","Sir Bob Russell","211601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100520","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-29","<p>Short Term Benefit Advances (STBA) are only available against legacy benefits. Universal Credit has it's own system of benefit advances. The equivalent support to STBA is provided by either the Universal Credit (new claim) advance or the Universal Credit (change of circumstance) advance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Currently these costs are not reported separately. UC benefit expenditure is published in the table in the attached link</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/benefit-expenditure-and-caseload-tables-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/benefit-expenditure-and-caseload-tables-2014</a></p><p> </p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-29T17:40:28.4640021Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100520/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100520/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100520/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-22","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much his Department spent on short term benefit advances for claimants of universal credit in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15 to date.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","211598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100521","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-28","<p>The information requested is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The number of people receiving Incapacity Benefit in Barnsley East constituency, Barnsley local authority and South Yorkshire area, as at February 2014.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Date</p></td><td><p>Barnsley East constituency</p></td><td><p>Barnsley local authority</p></td><td><p>South Yorkshire</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Feb-14</p></td><td><p>470</p></td><td><p>1,160</p></td><td><p>4,920</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Source:</p><p> </p><p>DWP 100% WPLS.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p> </p><p>1. Figures have been rounded to the nearest 10.</p><p> </p><p>2. Data is up to February 2014 which is the latest data available.</p><p> </p><p>3. Figures for South Yorkshire is the sum of Barnsley, Doncaster, Rotherham and Sheffield Local Authorities.</p><p> </p><p>4. These statistics are published at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dwp-statistics-tabulation-tool" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dwp-statistics-tabulation-tool</a></p><p> </p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-28T14:48:25.2189499Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100521/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100521/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100521/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-22","Incapacity Benefit: South Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in (a) Barnsley East constituency, (b) Barnsley local authority and (c) South Yorkshire are in receipt of incapacity benefit.","false","Biography information for Michael Dugher","Barnsley East","Michael Dugher","211599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100522","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-20","<p>While the Government checks the immigration status of benefit claimants to ensure the benefit is paid properly and to prevent fraud, traditionally that information has not been collected as part of the payment administrative systems.</p><p> </p><p>However, the Government is looking at ways to reform the current administrative system under Universal Credit so that it will systematically record nationality and immigration status of migrants who make a claim.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has made a radical series of changes over the last year to restrict the access by non-UK citizens from the European Economic Area to UK benefits and tax credits. This is in order to protect the UK’s benefit system and discourage people who have no established connection with the UK from moving here, unless they have a job or a genuine prospect of work, or have savings to support themselves until they do.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-11-20T17:39:50.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100522/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100522/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100522/answer","Wirral West","Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100522/answer/previousversion/24559","Biography information for Esther McVey","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-22","Social Security Benefits: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of paying in-work benefits to non-UK citizens from (a) other EU countries and (b) the rest of the world in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","211618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100523","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-03","<p>HMRC is responsible for handling calls to the Tax Credits helpline but is unable to distinguish, at the point of contact with its telephone system, if a caller is on a low income or otherwise.</p><p> </p><p>To keep the cost of dealing with HMRC as low as possible, the department has made it cheaper to call in most cases by rolling out 03 telephone numbers and by introducing voice recognition technology to its telephone systems, this allows some customers to get the answer they need without waiting to speak to adviser.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC recognises that wait times across all lines of business are not where it, or its customers, would like them to be. Over the next few months HMRC will be migrating its existing telephone services to a new telephony platform. This will improve the way that the queuing systems work and over time, will lead to reduced wait times.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC is also looking at a number of initiatives to improve customer service and wait times. These include: greater flexible working across HMRC to improve its response to particular peaks in demand and is investing in online and digital services for the future, opening up a wider variety of channels.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2014-11-03T14:50:04.3108469Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100523/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100523/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100523/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-10-22","Welfare Tax Credits: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will take steps to reduce waiting times experienced by (a) people on a low income and (b) other people using the HM Revenue and Customs tax credits helpline.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","211582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100524","Cabinet Office","false","2014-10-27","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2014-10-27T14:46:29.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100524/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100524/answer","PQ 211614 ONS 365.pdf","PQ 211614 ONS 365.pdf","ONS Letter to Member - Youth Unemployment","ONS Letter to Member - Youth Unemployment","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100524/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-10-22","Unemployment: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the level of youth unemployment in Pendle constituency in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","211614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100525","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-29","<p /> <p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-29T17:43:59.4241546Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100525/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100525/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100525/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-22","Employment and Support Allowance: South Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people currently in receipt of employment and support allowance (ESA) in (a) Barnsley East constituency, (b) Barnsley local authority and (c) South Yorkshire have been waiting more than 13 weeks for an ESA reassessment.","false","Biography information for Michael Dugher","Barnsley East","Michael Dugher","211630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100526","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-29","<p /> <p>The Jobseekers (Back to Work Schemes) Act 2013, required the Secretary of State to appoint an independent person to prepare a report on the operation of sanctions validated by the legislation. The terms of reference reflect this requirement.</p><p>However, the Government Response to the Oakley Review goes wider than the terms of reference. For example, we are reviewing all claimant communications and sanctions processes, not only for those Jobseekers Allowance claimants who come under the remit of the Report, but all JSA claimants and also all Employment Support Allowance claimants.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-10-29T14:49:03.8815563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100526/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100526/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100526/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-22","Jobseeker's Allowance Sanctions Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons the terms of reference for Matthew Oakley's review of jobseeker's allowance sanctions omitted sanctions for employment and support allowance.","false","Biography information for John Hemming","Birmingham, Yardley","John Hemming","211634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100527","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-28","<p>The information is not available. Such information as is available on the number of people in receipt of DLA, by parliamentary constituency and local authority can be extracted using the DWP Tabtool: <a href="http://83.244.183.180/100pc/tabtool.html" target="_blank">http://83.244.183.180/100pc/tabtool.html</a></p><p> </p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-28T17:46:04.4590779Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100527/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100527/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100527/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-22","Disability Living Allowance: South Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in (a) Barnsley East constituency, (b) Barnsley local authority and (c) South Yorkshire claimed disability living allowance in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Michael Dugher","Barnsley East","Michael Dugher","211633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100528","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-30","<p>HM Treasury approved the Universal Credit Strategic Outline Business Case in July 2011 and an updated business case in September 2014, as referred to on page 32 of the publication ‘Universal Credit at Work’. HM Treasury are the sole approval authority for Departmental business cases.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-30T14:10:31.6889256Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100528/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100528/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100528/answer","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/100528/answer/previousversion/24592","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-22","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the approved July 2011 business case for universal credit referred to on page 32 of his Department's publication, Universal Credit at Work, published in October 2014, was approved by (a) the Major Projects Authority and (b) HM Treasury; and whether that business case was a strategic outline business case or a full business case.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","211588"
